ion pounds from Jewish businessmen in recent years. But relations have been strained over the fallout from the Iraq war and British foreign policy in the Middle East. The Lib Dems have denied an attack on Ken Livingstone - the independent candidate for London mayor - was anti-Semitic. Lib Dem leader Simon Hughes accused the mayor of being \"an anti-Semitic apologist\" after he compared a Jewish Evening Standard journalist to a \"concentration camp guard\". But Mr Livingstone has since apologised for the comments. The Board of Deputies of British Jews, which had reported the mayor to the Standards Board for England over the incident, accepted Mr Livingstone's apology. Its president Henry Grunwald said: \"Oliver Finegold was deeply hurt by the mayor's remarks and we are pleased they have now been withdrawn.\"",
